Preparation and Overview

The quality of red wine is determined by many factors. Because each red wine has components in different concentration, the red wine is likely to taste differently from brand to brand. A red wine connoisseur can usually tell the age, the quality, maybe even the name of the wine. People who know how to examine the quality of a red wine are usually considered elegant and noble. Sometimes, if people know nothing about wine, they will probably purchase red wine in bad quality for their grand event. If people just want to throw a small party, it is unwise to buy the best red wine. To solve this problem, in this lab, we will use a machine learning training model to become the wine connoisseur. We will use a dataset of red wine. This dataset is related to red variants of the Portuguese "Vinho Verde" wine. In our training process, we will classify the red wines into three quality classes: "Good", "Medium", and "Bad".

Like mentioned earlier, any party host will be interested in our results. Using our results, he/she will have freedom to choose the quality of wine for the upcoming party. Also, any wine taster will be interested in our product because it can be used to train his/her tastebuds. Most importantly, red wine manufacturers will be interested so that they can know what quality they have and know how to improve the quality by adjusting the recipe.

Our training model will mainly be deployed in real-time because the whole dataset is the same type of wine and our model is just for this specific brand. The quality or grade varies by time and storing condition.

Source: https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/red-wine-quality-cortez-et-al-2009

Measure of Success

Our prediction task will be to "grade" the different red wine. Despite wine experts lauding their tastebuds and elevated senses, a study conducted by Robert Hodgson proved otherwise. He approached the organizers of the California state fair wine competition and asked them to present judges with different samples from the same bottle three times. Normally, judges scale a wine from range 50-100. He claims the results were "disturbing". After giving the judges samples from the same wine bottle, he found that they each scored it differently each time! Ranging from low 80s to high 90s, the expert judges (winemakers, sommeliers, critics and wine consultants and academics) were highly inconsistent. He further went on to say that objectively evaluating large numbers of wines as currently attempted at wine competitions is, "beyond human ability". Due to this fact that not even "experts" can consistently and accurately identify and grade wines, our goal is to reach 70% accuracy.

Source: https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2013/jun/23/wine-tasting-junk-science-analysis and https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blind_wine_tasting

Data Understanding

  • fixed acidity(float): the fixed acidity of most acids involved with wine
  • volatile(float): the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste
  • citric acid(float): found in small quantities, citric acid can add 'freshness' and flavor to wines
  • residual sugar(float): the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops
  • chlorides(float): the amount of salt in the wine
  • free sulfur dioxide(float): the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion
  • total sulfur dioxide(float): amount of free and bound forms of S02
  • density(float): the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content
  • pH(float): describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic)
  • sulphates(float): a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) level
  • alcohol(float): the percent alcohol content of the wine
  • quality(int,ordinal): The actual quality of the wine, ranging from 0-10
  • class(int,ordinal): Our prediction, there are three classes: 0, 1, 2.

Modeling

Below is the code base that Professor Larson had covered in the class. We will use this code to build a one-versus-all logistic regression classifier which includes three different kinds of methods: *Steepest, Stochastic, Newton* for updating gradiants. Then we will also add the regularization option when an object is being intializaed. The user can either use L1, L2, or both L1 and L2 to prevent overfitting the model

In [3]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from scipy.special import expit
import numpy as np
class BinaryLogisticRegressionBase:
    # private:
    def __init__(self, eta, iterations=20):
        self.eta = eta
        self.iters = iterations
        # internally we will store the weights as self.w_ to keep with sklearn conventions
    
    def __str__(self):
        return 'Base Binary Logistic Regression Object, Not Trainable'
    
    # convenience, private and static:
    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(theta):
        return 1/(1+np.exp(-theta)) 
    
    @staticmethod
    def _add_bias(X):
        return np.hstack((np.ones((X.shape[0],1)),X)) # add bias term
    
    # public:
    def predict_proba(self,X,add_bias=True):
        # add bias term if requested
        Xb = self._add_bias(X) if add_bias else X
        return self._sigmoid(Xb @ self.w_) # return the probability y=1
    
    def predict(self,X):
        return (self.predict_proba(X)>0.5) #return the actual prediction

class BinaryLogisticRegression(BinaryLogisticRegressionBase):
    #private:
    def __str__(self):
        if(hasattr(self,'w_')):
            return 'Binary Logistic Regression Object with coefficients:\n'+ str(self.w_) # is we have trained the object
        else:
            return 'Untrained Binary Logistic Regression Object'
        
    def _get_gradient(self,X,y):
        # programming \sum_i (yi-g(xi))xi
        gradient = np.zeros(self.w_.shape) # set gradient to zero
        for (xi,yi) in zip(X,y):
            # the actual update inside of sum
            gradi = (yi - self.predict_proba(xi,add_bias=False))*xi 
            # reshape to be column vector and add to gradient
            gradient += gradi.reshape(self.w_.shape) 
        
        return gradient/float(len(y))
       
    # public:
    def fit(self, X, y):
        Xb = self._add_bias(X) # add bias term
        num_samples, num_features = Xb.shape
        
        self.w_ = np.zeros((num_features,1)) # init weight vector to zeros
        
        # for as many as the max iterations
        for _ in range(self.iters):
            gradient = self._get_gradient(Xb,y)
            self.w_ += gradient*self.eta # multiply by learning rate 

class VectorBinaryLogisticRegression(BinaryLogisticRegression):
    # inherit from our previous class to get same functionality
    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(theta):
        # increase stability, redefine sigmoid operation
        return expit(theta) #1/(1+np.exp(-theta))
    
    # but overwrite the gradient calculation
    def _get_gradient(self,X,y):
        ydiff = y-self.predict_proba(X,add_bias=False).ravel() # get y difference
        gradient = np.mean(X * ydiff[:,np.newaxis], axis=0) # make ydiff a column vector and multiply through
        
        return gradient.reshape(self.w_.shape)

class LogisticRegression:
    def __init__(self, eta, iterations=20):
        self.eta = eta
        self.iters = iterations
        # internally we will store the weights as self.w_ to keep with sklearn conventions
    
    def __str__(self):
        if(hasattr(self,'w_')):
            return 'MultiClass Logistic Regression Object with coefficients:\n'+ str(self.w_) # is we have trained the object
        else:
            return 'Untrained MultiClass Logistic Regression Object'
        
    def fit(self,X,y):
        num_samples, num_features = X.shape
        self.unique_ = np.unique(y) # get each unique class value
        num_unique_classes = len(self.unique_)
        self.classifiers_ = [] # will fill this array with binary classifiers
        
        for i,yval in enumerate(self.unique_): # for each unique value
            y_binary = y==yval # create a binary problem
            # train the binary classifier for this class
            blr = VectorBinaryLogisticRegression(self.eta,self.iters)
            blr.fit(X,y_binary)
            # add the trained classifier to the list
            self.classifiers_.append(blr)
            
        # save all the weights into one matrix, separate column for each class
        self.w_ = np.hstack([x.w_ for x in self.classifiers_]).T
        
    def predict_proba(self,X):
        probs = []
        for blr in self.classifiers_:
            probs.append(blr.predict_proba(X)) # get probability for each classifier
        
        return np.hstack(probs) # make into single matrix
    
    def predict(self,X):
        return np.argmax(self.predict_proba(X),axis=1) # take argmax along row

class AdvancedLogisticRegression(LogisticRegression):
    def __init__(self, eta,reg=None,method=None,iterations=20, C=0.001):
        self.eta = eta
        self.reg = reg
        self.method = method
        self.iters = iterations
        self.C = C
        
    def fit(self,X,y):
        num_samples, num_features = X.shape
        self.unique_ = np.unique(y) # get each unique class value
        num_unique_classes = len(self.unique_)
        self.classifiers_ = [] # will fill this array with binary classifiers
        
        for i,yval in enumerate(self.unique_): # for each unique value
            y_binary = y==yval # create a binary problem
            # train the binary classifier for this class
            blr = AdvancedVectorBinaryLogisticRegression(self.eta,self.reg,self.method,self.iters,self.C)
            blr.fit(X,y_binary)
            # add the trained classifier to the list
            self.classifiers_.append(blr)
            
        # save all the weights into one matrix, separate column for each class
        self.w_ = np.hstack([x.w_ for x in self.classifiers_]).T
        
class AdvancedVectorBinaryLogisticRegression(VectorBinaryLogisticRegression):
    def __init__(self, eta,reg=None,method=None,iterations=20, C=0.001):
        self.eta = eta
        self.reg = reg
        self.method = method
        self.iters = iterations
        self.C = C
    def _get_gradient(self,X,y):
        if(self.method=='stochastic'):
            idx = int(np.random.rand()*len(y)) # grab random instance
            ydiff = y[idx]-self.predict_proba(X[idx],add_bias=False) # get y difference (now scalar)
            gradient = X[idx] * ydiff[:,np.newaxis] # make ydiff a column vector and multiply through
            gradient = gradient.reshape(self.w_.shape)
        elif(self.method=='newton'):
            g = self.predict_proba(X,add_bias=False).ravel() # get sigmoid value for all classes
            hessian = X.T @ np.diag(g*(1-g)) @ X - 2 * self.C # calculate the hessian

            ydiff = y-g # get y difference
            gradient = np.sum(X * ydiff[:,np.newaxis], axis=0) # make ydiff a column vector and multiply through
            gradient = gradient.reshape(self.w_.shape)
        else:
            ydiff = y-self.predict_proba(X,add_bias=False).ravel() # get y difference
            gradient = np.mean(X * ydiff[:,np.newaxis], axis=0) # make ydiff a column vector and multiply through
            gradient = gradient.reshape(self.w_.shape) 
        
        if self.reg == 'L1':
            # L1 = C * sum(|w|)
            gradient[1:] += -self.C * np.sum(abs(self.w_[1:])) 
        elif(self.reg == 'L2'):
            # L2 = C * sum(|w|^2)
            gradient[1:] += -2 * self.w_[1:] ** 2 * self.C
        elif self.reg == 'L3':
            gradient[1:] += -self.C * np.sum(abs(self.w_[1:]))
            gradient[1:] += -2 * self.w_[1:] ** 2 * self.C
        return gradient

Now we need to implement an improved version of logistic regression classifier for our dataset. We created an 'AdvancedLogisticRegression' object which inherits LogisticRegression and changes the constructor method and overwrites the fit function. Now it can recieve two more parameteres: one for regularization and one for the gradiant function. We also made the 'AdvancedVectorBinaryLogisticRegression' which will be created when the users run the fit function of an AdvancedLogisticRegression object.

Training Stage

Now it is time to train the classifier to achieve good generalization performance. We will slightly change eta or cost or iteration per loop to find the optimal classifier.

from mpl_toolkits import mplot3d
%matplotlib inline
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot_performance(x,y,z,k,method):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
    fig.suptitle(method+' method accuracy,time versus eta and cost')
    ax = fig.add_subplot(1,2,1,projection='3d')
    plt.title('Accuracy')
    ax.scatter3D(x, y, z,
                 cmap='viridis', edgecolor='none');
    ax.set_xlabel('eta_value')
    ax.set_ylabel('cost_value')
    ax.set_zlabel('accuracy');

    ax = fig.add_subplot(1,2,2,projection='3d')
    plt.title('Time')
    ax.scatter3D(x,y,k,
                 cmap='viridis', edgecolor='none');
    ax.set_xlabel('eta_value')
    ax.set_ylabel('cost_value')
    ax.set_zlabel('time');

Recommandation

We would still recommend using scikit-learn. Like mentioned earlier, a blind guess in quality "2" could have an accuracy of 0.52, so our training model does not improve much on accuracy. Scikit-learn, however, pushes the accuracy to 70%. In addition, our training model, because it uses stochastic method, the performance is not very stable. Sometimes the accuracy would drop to 50% or even 40%, but scikit-learn's performance is very stable. Finally, regarding time, It is true our training model runs four times faster than scikit-learn and we would have our training model be real-time analysis. However, 21ms, which is time cost of scikit learn, is fast enough to be a real-time analyzer.

We failed to reach the accuracy of 70% that makes our algorithm useful and scikit-learn reached that accuracy

Code Below is used to extract rows and make pairs. The index array called index helps us rearrange the result. All the binary logistic regression objects will be stored in the classifiers array for future predict

For one-versus_one, we will first extract rows whose quality include only 0 and 1, then extract rows whose quality 0 and 2, we will use vector binary logistic regression to determine the result and then use the intersection of these two results to get prediction for class 0. Then we will do another vector binary logistic regression training for rows whose quality 1 and 2 and get the overall yhat.

class OvOLogisticRegression:
    def __init__(self, eta, iterations=20):
        self.eta = eta
        self.iters = iterations
        # internally we will store the weights as self.w_ to keep with sklearn conventions
    
    def __str__(self):
        if(hasattr(self,'w_')):
            return 'MultiClass Logistic Regression Object with coefficients:\n'+ str(self.w_) # is we have trained the object
        else:
            return 'Untrained MultiClass Logistic Regression Object'
        
    def fit(self,X,y):
        num_samples, num_features = X.shape
        self.unique_ = np.unique(y) # get each unique class value
        num_unique_classes = len(self.unique_)
        self.classifiers_ = [] # will fill this array with binary classifiers
        
        y_hat=np.empty(len(y))
        for i in range(0,len(y_hat)):
            y_hat[i]=-1
            INDEX=np.array(df['index'])
        for i in range(0,num_unique_classes-1):
            Binary_List=[]
            Target_List=[]
            Index_List=[]
            yhat_list=[]
            result_list=[]
            for j in range(i+1,num_unique_classes,1):

                df_binary1=df[df['class']==self.unique_[i]]
                df_binary2=df[df['class']==self.unique_[j]]
                df_binary=pd.concat([df_binary1,df_binary2])
                target=df_binary['class']==self.unique_[i]
                index=np.array(df_binary['index'])
                Binary_List.append(df_binary)
                Target_List.append(target)
                Index_List.append(index)
                
            num=len(Binary_List)
            for k in range(0,num):
                blr = VectorBinaryLogisticRegression(self.eta,self.iters)
                blr.fit(Binary_List[k],Target_List[k])
                self.classifiers_.append(blr)
    
        
    def predict(self,X):
        num_unique_classes = len(self.unique_)
        y_hat=np.empty(len(X))
        
        count=0
        for i in range(0,len(y_hat)):
            y_hat[i]=-1
            INDEX=np.array(df['index'])
        for i in range(0,num_unique_classes-1):
            Binary_List=[]
            Index_List=[]
            yhat_list=[]
            result_list=[]
            for j in range(i+1,num_unique_classes,1):
                df_binary1=df[df['class']==self.unique_[i]]
                df_binary2=df[df['class']==self.unique_[j]]
                df_binary=pd.concat([df_binary1,df_binary2])
                index=np.array(df_binary['index'])
                Binary_List.append(df_binary)
                Index_List.append(index)
            num=len(Binary_List)
            for k in range(0,num):                
                yhat = self.classifiers_[count].predict(Binary_List[k])
                count+=1                
                yhat_list.append(yhat)
                result=[]
                        
                for m in range(0,len(yhat)):
                    if yhat[m]==True:
                        result.append(Index_List[k][m])
                result_list.append(result)
                
            final_y=result_list[0]
            
            for n in range(1,len(result_list)):
                final_y=(list(set(final_y).intersection(result_list[n])))
            for v in range(0,len(INDEX)):
                if INDEX[v] in final_y:
                    y_hat[v]=self.unique_[i]
            
        
        for i in range(0,len(y_hat)):
            if y_hat[i] ==-1:
                y_hat[i]=2
                
        return y_hat

from numpy.linalg import pinv
class HessianBinaryLogisticRegression(BinaryLogisticRegression):
    
    # overwrite gradient function
    def _get_gradient(self,X,y):
        
        g = self.predict_proba(X,add_bias=False).ravel() 
        hessian = X.T @ np.diag(g*(1-g)*(y - 2*y*g + 2*g + 3*g**2)) @ X # calculate the hessian

        ydiff = (y-g)*g*(1-g) 
        gradient = np.sum(X * ydiff[:,np.newaxis], axis=0)
        gradient = gradient.reshape(self.w_.shape)
        
        return pinv(hessian) @ gradient
       


# training

hlr.fit(X,y)

In this part, we overwrite a function and calculate the hessian to get gradient. And then train the classfier and get the train accuracy and test accuracy. The hessian calculation use MSE(Mean squared error) function to get the answer. And in the code block we implement it for get gradient function
